data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET Core/.NET 5+. It was removed because it could corrupt application state by unwinding the stack at arbitrary points.
2. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.
3. **`ThreadAbortException` is never raised** — catching it is dead code.

### The Core Problem

`Thread.Abort()` was the only mechanism to forcibly terminate uncooperative code. .NET 8 has **no equivalent**. The modern pattern requires **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate MUST observe the CancellationToken for
    /// timeout to actually stop execution.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Overload for synchronous work. Runs on the thread pool.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return await ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
            ct => Task.Run(() => work(ct), ct),
            timeout);
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Fire-and-forget variant: abandons (but cannot kill) work that
    /// ignores the CancellationToken. Use only when you accept that
    /// the work may keep running in the background after timeout.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutOrAbandonAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        var task = Task.Run(work);
        var completed = await Task.WhenAny(task, Task.Delay(timeout));

        if (completed != task)
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");

        return await task; // Unwraps any exception
    }
}
```

### Usage Examples

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// 1. Async work (preferred) — fully cancellable
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(async ct =>
{
    await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, ct);  // observes token
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// 2. Sync CPU work — cancellable via token checks
var sum = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(ct =>
{
    long total = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000_000; i++)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // cooperative check
        total += i;
    }
    return total;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));

// 3. Legacy uncooperative code — abandoned on timeout (NOT killed)
var data = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutOrAbandonAsync(
    () => SomeLegacyBlockingCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **No forced termination** | Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, nothing in .NET 8 can kill a thread. Uncooperative code keeps running after "timeout". |
| **Sync-over-async deadlock** | Don't call `.Result` or `.Wait()` on these from a UI/ASP.NET sync context — use `await`. |
| **`Task.Run` + abandon = leak** | `ExecuteWithTimeoutOrAbandonAsync` leaks the thread if work never finishes. Use only as a last resort for legacy code you can't modify. |
| **`default(T)` was a bug** | The original code returned `default` if `thread.Join` returned `true` but the work threw — the new code propagates exceptions correctly via `await`. |
| **Process-level isolation** | If you truly need to kill uncooperative code, run it in a **separate process** and kill the process on timeout. |

### If You Truly Need Hard Kill (Process Isolation)

```csharp
// Last resort: run untrusted/uncooperative code out-of-process
using var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("Worker process timed out");
}
```

**Bottom line:** Replace `Thread.Abort` with `CancellationToken` everywhere. If the work can't be modified to accept a token, you must choose between abandoning it (leak risk) or process isolation (complexity cost).
